04503nam a22005655i 9780773587007DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735870077 a10.1515/97807735870072doi  a(DE-B1597)655796  a(OCoLC)1320966074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aARC0160002bisacsh04a726.5/09711 aMagrill, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommerce of Taste :bChurch Architecture in Canada, 1867-1914 /cBarry Magrill. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b21 bw photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v5600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Rise of Commercial Society in Pre-Confederation Canada -- tEconomy and Religion from the Maritimes to Upper Canada -- tSelling Ecclesiology as Identity in the Dominion of Canada -- tProperty Ownership and Church-Building: The Financial Structure of Churches in Ontario -- tThe Spread of Empire in Western Canada: Railway, Religion, and Church-Building -- tAn Unfinished Business of Western Expansion -- tThe Influence of us Artistic, Cultural, and Economic Capital -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Biographies of Pattern Book Authors -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late-nineteenth century the circulation of pattern books featuring medieval church architecture in England facilitated an unprecedented spread of Gothic revival churches in Canada. Engaging several themes around the spread of print culture, religion, and settlement, A Commerce of Taste details the business of church building. Drawing upon formal architectural analysis and cultural theory, Barry Magrill shows how pattern books offer a unique way of studying the relationships between taste, ideology, privilege, social change, and economics. Taste was a concept used to legitimize British - and to an extent Anglican - privilege, while other denominations resisted their aesthetic edicts. Pattern books eventually lost control of the exclusivity associated with taste as advances in printing technology and transatlantic shipping brought more books into the marketplace and readerships expanded beyond the professional classes. By the early twentieth century taste had become diluted, the architect had lost his heroic status, and architectural distinctions among denominations were less apparent. Drawing together the history of church building and the broader patterns of Canadian social and historical development, A Commerce of Taste presents an alternative perspective on the spread of religious monuments in Canada by looking squarely at pattern books as sources of social conflict around the issue of taste.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada-Economic conditions-19th century. 0aCanada-Social conditions-19th century. 0aGothic revival (Architecture)-Canada. 0aPattern books-Great Britain. 0aReligious architecture-Canada. 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358700740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587007423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587007/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles